<style type="text/css">

.tocify {
width: 20%;
max-height: 90%;
overflow: auto;
margin-left: 2%;
position: fixed;
border: 1px solid #ccc;
border-radius: 6px;
}

.tocify ul, .tocify li {
list-style: none;
margin: 0;
padding: 0;
border: none;
line-height: 30px;
}

.tocify-header {
text-indent: 10px;
}

.tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 20px;
display: none;
}

.tocify-subheader li {
font-size: 12px;
}

.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 30px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 40px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 50px;
}
.tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader .tocify-subheader {
text-indent: 60px;
}

.tocify .tocify-item > a, .tocify .nav-list .nav-header {
margin: 0px;
}

.tocify .tocify-item a, .tocify .list-group-item {
padding: 5px;
}
.tocify .nav-pills > li {
float: none;
}


</style>

    tabs.each(function(i) {

      // get the tab div
      var tab = $(tabs[i]);

      // get the id then sanitize it for use with bootstrap tabs
      var id = tab.attr('id');

      // see if this is marked as the active tab
      if (tab.hasClass('active'))
        activeTab = i;

      // remove any table of contents entries associated with
      // this ID (since we'll be removing the heading element)
      $("div#" + tocID + " li a[href='#" + id + "']").parent().remove();

      // sanitize the id for use with bootstrap tabs
      id = id.replace(/[.\/?&!#<>]/g, '').replace(/\s/g, '_');
      tab.attr('id', id);

      // get the heading element within it, grab it's text, then remove it
      var heading = tab.find('h' + tabLevel + ':first');
      var headingText = heading.html();
      heading.remove();

      // build and append the tab list item
      var a = $('<a role="tab" data-toggle="tab">' + headingText + '</a>');
      a.attr('href', '#' + id);
      a.attr('aria-controls', id);
      var li = $('<li role="presentation"></li>');
      li.append(a);
      tabList.append(li);

      // set it's attributes
      tab.attr('role', 'tabpanel');
      tab.addClass('tab-pane');
      tab.addClass('tabbed-pane');
      if (fade)
        tab.addClass('fade');

      // move it into the tab content div
      tab.detach().appendTo(tabContent);
    });

    // set active tab
    $(tabList.children('li')[activeTab]).addClass('active');
    var active = $(tabContent.children('div.section')[activeTab]);
    active.addClass('active');
    if (fade)
      active.addClass('in');

    if (tabset.hasClass("tabset-sticky"))
      tabset.rmarkdownStickyTabs();
  }

  // convert section divs with the .tabset class to tabsets
  var tabsets = $("div.section.tabset");
  tabsets.each(function(i) {
    buildTabset($(tabsets[i]));
  });
};

</script>
<script>
window.initializeCodeFolding = function(show) {

  // handlers for show-all and hide all
  $("#rmd-show-all-code").click(function() {
    $('div.r-code-collapse').each(function() {
      $(this).collapse('show');
    });
  });
  $("#rmd-hide-all-code").click(function() {
    $('div.r-code-collapse').each(function() {
      $(this).collapse('hide');
    });
  });

  // index for unique code element ids
  var currentIndex = 1;

  // select all R code blocks
  var rCodeBlocks = $('pre.r, pre.python, pre.bash, pre.sql, pre.cpp, pre.stan, pre.julia, pre.foldable');
  rCodeBlocks.each(function() {
    // skip if the block has fold-none class
    if ($(this).hasClass('fold-none')) return;

    // create a collapsable div to wrap the code in
    var div = $('<div class="collapse r-code-collapse"></div>');
    var showThis = (show || $(this).hasClass('fold-show')) && !$(this).hasClass('fold-hide');
    var id = 'rcode-643E0F36' + currentIndex++;
    div.attr('id', id);
    $(this).before(div);
    $(this).detach().appendTo(div);

    // add a show code button right above
    var showCodeText = $('<span>' + (showThis ? 'Hide' : 'Show') + '</span>');
    var showCodeButton = $('<button type="button" class="btn btn-default btn-xs btn-secondary btn-sm code-folding-btn pull-right float-right"></button>');
    showCodeButton.append(showCodeText);
    showCodeButton
        .attr('data-toggle', 'collapse')
        .attr('data-bs-toggle', 'collapse') // BS5
        .attr('data-target', '#' + id)
        .attr('data-bs-target', '#' + id)   // BS5
        .attr('aria-expanded', showThis)
        .attr('aria-controls', id);

    var buttonRow = $('<div class="row"></div>');
    var buttonCol = $('<div class="col-md-12"></div>');

    buttonCol.append(showCodeButton);
    buttonRow.append(buttonCol);

    div.before(buttonRow);

    // show the div if necessary
    if (showThis) div.collapse('show');

    // update state of button on show/hide
    //   * Change text
    //   * add a class for intermediate states styling
    div.on('hide.bs.collapse', function () {
      showCodeText.text('Show');
      showCodeButton.addClass('btn-collapsing');
    });
    div.on('hidden.bs.collapse', function () {
      showCodeButton.removeClass('btn-collapsing');
    });
    div.on('show.bs.collapse', function () {
      showCodeText.text('Hide');
      showCodeButton.addClass('btn-expanding');
    });
    div.on('shown.bs.collapse', function () {
      showCodeButton.removeClass('btn-expanding');
    });

  });

}
</script>

<h1 class="title toc-ignore">Interpretable time-series modelling using
Gaussian processes</h1>
<h4 class="author">Trent Henderson</h4>
<h4 class="date">2024-05-02</h4>

</div>


<div id="introduction" class="section level1" number="1">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">1</span> Introduction</h1>
<p>Welcome! If it wasn’t already obvious, I love time-series analysis,
so we are going to dive deep into it here. Another thing I love is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_process">Gaussian
processes</a> (GP), so why not combine the two?! We’ll get into the
details later, but GPs are an insanely powerful tool that can model an
absurd range of data (including continuous and discrete) in an
interpretable way that gives the modeller a large degree of control over
how the technique <em>learns</em> from data. This makes GPs an
invaluable tool in any applied statistician/machine learning
practitioner’s toolkit.</p>
<p>It is important to remember that using a GP for time series basically
converts the problem from one of modelling a <em>generative process</em>
(e.g., if we used an <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autoregressive_integrated_moving_average">ARIMA</a>
model) to that of essentially a curve-fitting exercise. GPs are a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bayesian_statistics">Bayesian</a>
method, so if you are unfamiliar with Bayesian inference, please go
check out some resources on that, such as <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=guTdrfycW2Q&amp;list=PLDcUM9US4XdMROZ57-OIRtIK0aOynbgZN&amp;index=4">this
great video</a> by Richard McElreath. Essentially, the key bits to
remember for this post is that in Bayesian inference, we are interested
in the posterior distribution, which is proportional to the product of
the prior (our beliefs about an event before seeing the data) and the
likelihood (the probability of the data given model parameters).
Throughout this post, we are going to build a basic GP from scratch to
highlight the intuition and mechanics underlying the modelling
process.</p>
<p>In practice, we would most likely fit GPs using a purpose-built tool,
such as coding one in the probabilistic programming language <a href="https://mc-stan.org">Stan</a> to utilise <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain_Monte_Carlo">Markov
chain Monte Carlo</a> for sampling, or using a dedicated GP package such
as <a href="https://gpy.readthedocs.io/en/deploy/">GPy</a>, <a href="https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/GauPro/vignettes/GauPro.html">GauPro</a>,
or even <a href="https://www.tensorflow.org/probability">Tensorflow
Probability</a>.</p>
<p>Before we get started, we will load the R packages we need:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>library(Rcpp)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(ggplot2)
library(nousstyle)
library(MASS)
library(TSA)</code></pre>
</div>
<div id="generating-some-data" class="section level1" number="2">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">2</span> Generating some
data</h1>
<p>We are going to simulate some time series data with temporal dynamics
that are commonly encountered in applied settings. Specifically, we are
going to generate a noisy sine wave (i.e., to emulate periodic or
seasonal data) with a linearly increasing trend:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>set.seed(123)
y &lt;- 3 * sin(2 * seq(0, 4 * pi, length.out = 100)) + runif(100) * 2
trend &lt;- 0.08 * seq(from = 1, to = 100, by = 1)
y &lt;- y + trend
tmp &lt;- data.frame(timepoint = 1:length(y), y = y)

# Draw plot

ggplot(data = tmp) +
  geom_point(aes(x = timepoint, y = y), colour = nous_colour(&quot;C5&quot;)) +
  geom_line(aes(x = timepoint, y = y), colour = nous_colour(&quot;C5&quot;)) +
  labs(x = &quot;Timepoint&quot;,
       y = &quot;Values&quot;) +
  theme_nous(gridlines = TRUE)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
</div>
<div id="decomposing-a-time-series-for-modelling" class="section level1" number="3">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">3</span> Decomposing a time
series for modelling</h1>
<p>There are a great many ways to do time-series analysis. A lot of it
hinges on the expected usage of the model, such as forecasting or
classification. In our case, we are interested in constructing a model
that can accurately capture temporal properties and generate sensible
predictions on which to do inference on. One approach for doing this is
known as <a href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0169716105800458">structural
time series</a>. Basically, this involves decomposing a time series into
the sum of simpler parts. Such a model might take the following
form:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
f(x) = f_{1}(x) + f_{2}(x) + \dots + f_{n}(x) + \epsilon
\]</span></p>
<p>where <span class="math inline">\(f_{1}(x) \dots f_{n}(x)\)</span>
are the different <em>parts</em> of the time series we are explicitly
modelling, and <span class="math inline">\(\epsilon\)</span> is the
error term. Examples of these parts may include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Trend — Is there an average increase/decrease over time?</li>
<li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autocorrelation">Autocorrelation</a>
structure — How correlated are points to those that came before it? At
which lag is this relationship meaningful (e.g., one point behind? Five
points behind?)?</li>
<li>Seasonality — Are there recurring periodicities in the data (e.g.,
cyclic patterns observed at a weekly and monthly level for retail
sales)?</li>
<li>Holidays — Are there infrequent holiday periods which are important
to capture? <em>We are going to ignore this here for
simplicity</em></li>
<li><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Likelihood_function">Likelihood</a>
— What probability distribution best describes my data (e.g., for
continuous data this might be a Gaussian, for count data it might be
Poisson or Negative Binomial, etc.)?</li>
</ul>
<p>Hopefully at this point the intention here is reasonably clear — we
can model time series in an extremely flexible and transparent manner
through the explicit modelling of various statistical processes describe
by the data. While a GP doesn’t look like the above equation, it is
important to keep this idea of components/parts in mind, as it will
become quite useful very soon after we unpack the mechanics of GPs.</p>
</div>
<div id="gaussian-processes" class="section level1" number="4">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">4</span> Gaussian processes</h1>
<p>The most general GP definition is that they are a <em>generalisation
of the multivariate normal distribution to an infinite number of
dimensions.</em> That is not super helpful… Let’s unpack it a bit.</p>
<p>Recall that a Gaussian distribution is parameterised by two scalar
values: (i) mean <span class="math inline">\(\mu\)</span>; and (ii)
variance <span class="math inline">\(\sigma^{2}\)</span> (or the
standard deviation which is the square root of the variance). We can
write it as:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[\mathcal{N}(\mu,
\sigma^{2})\]</span></p>
<p>We can increase the dimensionality of this univariate case to
describe <em>multivariate Gaussian distributions</em>, by increasing the
dimensionality of the parameters. This results in our mean becoming a
mean vector <span class="math inline">\(\mu\)</span> and our variance
becoming a <em>covariance matrix</em> <span class="math inline">\(\Sigma\)</span> (as we now need to describe both
the variance of each variable and the covariance between them), written
as:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[\textbf{X} \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu,
\Sigma)\]</span></p>
<p>A GP, by its broad definition, is just a generalisation of this idea
to an infinite number of dimensions. This means our mean vector and
covariance matrix become a <em>mean </em>function* <span class="math inline">\(m(x)\)</span> and covariance <em>function</em>
<span class="math inline">\(k(x, x&#39;)\)</span> (also called a
‘kernel’). See how we have abstracted from scalar values to functions
without changing the broad underlying idea? Putting this all together,
we have the general form of a GP:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
f(x) = \mathcal{GP}(m(x), k(x, x&#39;))
\]</span></p>
<p>Now, it turns out that for most applications the mean function plays
a relatively minor role in contributing to the outputs of a GP. In other
words, almost all of the details are driven by the covariance function.
Practically, this means that oftentimes <span class="math inline">\(m(x)\)</span> is just set to <span class="math inline">\(0\)</span>. In contrast, by specifying different
covariance functions, we can exercise substantial control over the
resulting model fit and predictions. This is where domain and
statistical expertise comes in.</p>
<p>There are a great number of covariance functions (noting that they
<strong>must</strong> be <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PositiveDefiniteMatrix.html">positive
definite</a> to be valid) available to us, and deciding on which of them
to use is a key aspect of the modelling process. In the GP regression
context, we specify a <em>prior</em> over functions using the kernel.
The process of Bayesian updating then occurs, resulting from the
considerations of both our prior and the likelihood (the data).</p>
<p>The following sections explore a few of the most common kernels you
might encounter. To demonstrate them, we are just going to generate a
bunch of data points in a constrained range (don’t worry, we’ll return
to our original time series soon!):</p>
<pre class="r"><code>x1 &lt;- seq(from = -2, to = 2, length.out = 100)</code></pre>
<div id="exponentiated-quadratic-kernel" class="section level2" number="4.1">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.1</span> Exponentiated
quadratic kernel</h2>
<p>This is by far the most common kernel (also known as “radial basis
function” or RBF or “squared exponential”), and even forms the basis for
simpler machine learning methods, such as RBF <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Support-vector_machine">support
vector machines</a> (SVM). One of the reasons for this is it is quite
similar to the formula for a univariate Gaussian distribution. We can
write it mathematically as:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
k(x, x&#39;) = \text{exp} \left( -\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}||x -
x&#39;||^{2} \right)
\]</span></p>
<p>where <span class="math inline">\(\sigma^{2}\)</span> is the variance
(average distance of a function away from its mean) and <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l}\)</span> is the lengthscale (the
length of the “wiggles” in a function). You can refer to these as
<em>hyperparameters</em> that we can set or learn to control the shape
of the kernel.</p>
<p>In R, we can code this manually (note we are using <a href="http://adv-r.had.co.nz/Rcpp.html"><code>Rcpp</code></a> for
computational efficiency):</p>
<pre class="r"><code>Rcpp::cppFunction(&quot;
NumericMatrix cov_exp_quad(NumericVector xa, NumericVector xb, double sigma, double l) {
  int n1 = xa.size();
  int n2 = xb.size();
  NumericMatrix K(n1, n2);
  
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; n1; ++i) {
    for (int j = 0; j &lt; n2; ++j) {
      double diff = xa[i] - xb[j];
      double exp_term = exp(-0.5 * pow(diff / l, 2));
      K(i, j) = pow(sigma, 2) * exp_term;
    }
  }
  
  return K;
}
&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>We can visualise the resulting matrix of this function on a subset of
datapoints from our vector <code>y</code>. Let’s say the first 5 points
for clarity:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_exp_quad &lt;- cov_exp_quad(x1, x1, 1, 1)
mat_exp_quad[1:5, 1:5]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##           [,1]      [,2]      [,3]      [,4]      [,5]
## [1,] 1.0000000 0.9991841 0.9967404 0.9926807 0.9870250
## [2,] 0.9991841 1.0000000 0.9991841 0.9967404 0.9926807
## [3,] 0.9967404 0.9991841 1.0000000 0.9991841 0.9967404
## [4,] 0.9926807 0.9967404 0.9991841 1.0000000 0.9991841
## [5,] 0.9870250 0.9926807 0.9967404 0.9991841 1.0000000</code></pre>
<p>We can see ones on the diagonal (variance with itself) and numbers
everywhere else (covariance). Beautiful. We can also confirm that it is
symmetrical:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>isSymmetric(mat_exp_quad)</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] TRUE</code></pre>
<p>We can generate some random samples from the kernel to visualise what
it looks like on its own (we are going to define a reusable function
here to use later — <em>note that most of this code is just data
wrangling and plotting — the actual GP mechanics only take 3
lines</em>):</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#&#39; Draw random samples from kernel (assumed mean vector is zero)
#&#39; @param n \code{integer} denoting number of observations
#&#39; @param k \code{integer} denoting number  of realisations to draw. Defaults to \code{5}
#&#39; @param mu \code{vector} for the mean. Defaults to \code{NULL} for a vector of zeros
#&#39; @param X \code{vector} of numeric values used to generate \code{Sigma}
#&#39; @param Sigma \code{matrix} of covariance
#&#39; @returns object of class \code{ggplot}
#&#39;

sample_kernel &lt;- function(n, k = 5, mu = NULL, X, Sigma){
  
  # Prepare mean vector if NULL
  
  if(is.null(mu)){
    mu &lt;- integer(length = n)
  }
  
  # Produce dynamic column names, draw from multivariate normal, and convert to dataframe
  
  thenames &lt;- list()
  
  for(i in 1:k){
    thenames[[i]] &lt;- paste0(&quot;Sample &quot;, i)
  }
  
  thenames &lt;- unlist(thenames)
  y &lt;- as.data.frame(t(MASS::mvrnorm(n = k, mu = mu, Sigma = Sigma)))
  colnames(y) &lt;- thenames
  draws &lt;- data.frame(x = X)
  draws &lt;- cbind(draws, y)
  
  # Wrangle into long format for ggplot
  
  draws &lt;- reshape(draws, direction = &quot;long&quot;,
                   v.names = &quot;y&quot;,
                   varying = 2:ncol(draws),
                   times = names(draws)[2:ncol(draws)],
                   timevar = &quot;sample_ind&quot;)
  
  # Draw plot
  
  p &lt;- ggplot(data = draws, aes(x = x, y = y, colour = sample_ind)) +
      geom_line(linewidth = 0.7) +
      labs(x = &quot;x&quot;,
           y = &quot;y = f(x)&quot;,
           colour = NULL) +
      theme_nous(gridlines = TRUE) +
      theme(legend.position = &quot;bottom&quot;)
  
  return(p)
}

p &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_exp_quad), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_exp_quad)
print(p)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Notice how these curves could realistically be using to model a
long-term effect (even non-linear ones), such as a trend? You might also
notice that they are essentially shaped like <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spline_(mathematics)">splines</a>
(similar to what is used in <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_additive_model">generalised
additive models</a>).</p>
<p>As another example, assume that for our data we believed the pattern
to be highly non-linear with substantial variation. Well, we can make
the lengthscale (<span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l}\)</span>)
shorter to increase the function “wiggliness” (yes, that’s the technical
term). Let’s try <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l} = 0.3\)</span>
instead of <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l} = 1\)</span> and see
what happens:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_exp_quad2 &lt;- cov_exp_quad(x1, x1, 1, 0.3)
p_b &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_exp_quad2), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_exp_quad2)
print(p_b)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Our resulting functions are now far more wiggly. Notice how the
statistical implementation follows directly from the conceptual
understanding of the data? This is the idea at the heart of
interpretable modelling.</p>
<p>Another way to visualise the covariance matrix is through a heatmap.
Here is a function to do that, and the plot for all hyperparameters set
to <span class="math inline">\(1\)</span>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#&#39; Convert covariance matrix to dataframe and plot
#&#39; @param matrix the covariance matrix
#&#39; @return object of class \code{ggplot}
#&#39; 

plot_covariance &lt;- function(matrix){
  
  mat_df &lt;- as.data.frame(matrix)
  mat_df$x &lt;- seq_len(nrow(mat_df))
  
  mat_df &lt;- reshape(mat_df, 
                    direction = &quot;long&quot;,
                    v.names = &quot;values&quot;,
                    varying = 1:(ncol(mat_df) - 1),
                    times = 1:nrow(mat_df),
                    idvar = &quot;x&quot;)
  
  p &lt;- ggplot(data = mat_df) +
    geom_tile(aes(x = x, y = time, fill = values)) +
    labs(title = &quot;Heatmap of covariance matrix&quot;,
         x = &quot;x&quot;,
         y = &quot;x&quot;,
         fill = &quot;k(x,x&#39;)&quot;) +
    scale_fill_viridis_c(limits = c(0, 1),
                         breaks = seq(from = 0, to = 1, by = 0.2)) +
    theme_nous(gridlines = TRUE) +
    theme(legend.position = &quot;bottom&quot;)
  
  return(p)
}

plot_covariance(matrix = mat_exp_quad)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
<p>And with the shorter lengthscale of <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l} = 0.3\)</span> for comparison:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot_covariance(matrix = mat_exp_quad2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
</div>
<div id="rational-quadratic-kernel" class="section level2" number="4.2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.2</span> Rational quadratic
kernel</h2>
<p>Another common kernel is the rational quadratic. You can think of
this as being equivalent to adding together many squared exponential
kernels with different lengthscales (credit to <a href="https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~duvenaud/cookbook/">this great
resource</a> for the brief description).</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
k(x, x&#39;) = \sigma^{2} \left( 1 + \frac{||x - x&#39;||^{2}}{2\alpha
\mathcal{l}^{2}} \right)^{-\alpha}
\]</span></p>
<p>where where <span class="math inline">\(\sigma^{2}\)</span> is the
variance, <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l}\)</span> is the
lengthscale, and <span class="math inline">\(\alpha\)</span> is the
mixing coefficient (where <span class="math inline">\(\alpha &gt;
0\)</span>).</p>
<p>We can code this in R as:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>cppFunction(&quot;
NumericMatrix cov_rat_quad(NumericVector xa, NumericVector xb, double sigma, double alpha, double l) {
  int n1 = xa.size();
  int n2 = xb.size();
  NumericMatrix K(n1, n2);
  
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; n1; ++i) {
    for (int j = 0; j &lt; n2; ++j) {
      double diff = xa[i] - xb[j];
      double norm_sq = pow(diff, 2);
      double exp_term = pow(1 + norm_sq / (2 * alpha * pow(l, 2)), -alpha);
      K(i, j) = pow(sigma, 2) * exp_term;
    }
  }
  
  return K;
}
&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Again, a sample of the matrix:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_rat_quad &lt;- cov_rat_quad(x1, x1, 1, 1, 1)
mat_rat_quad[1:5, 1:5]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##           [,1]      [,2]      [,3]      [,4]      [,5]
## [1,] 1.0000000 0.9991844 0.9967457 0.9927074 0.9871085
## [2,] 0.9991844 1.0000000 0.9991844 0.9967457 0.9927074
## [3,] 0.9967457 0.9991844 1.0000000 0.9991844 0.9967457
## [4,] 0.9927074 0.9967457 0.9991844 1.0000000 0.9991844
## [5,] 0.9871085 0.9927074 0.9967457 0.9991844 1.0000000</code></pre>
<p>And some random samples from the kernel:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>p1 &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_rat_quad), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_rat_quad)
print(p1)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Note that again we can control wiggliness through lengthscale <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l}\)</span> but also now <span class="math inline">\(\alpha\)</span> here too. Here is a reduction in
<span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l}\)</span>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_rat_quad2 &lt;- cov_rat_quad(x1, x1, 1, 1, 0.3)
p1_b &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_rat_quad2), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_rat_quad2)
print(p1_b)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>And here is a reduction in <span class="math inline">\(\alpha\)</span>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_rat_quad3 &lt;- cov_rat_quad(x1, x1, 1, 0.1, 1)
p1_c &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_rat_quad3), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_rat_quad3)
print(p1_c)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Finally, we can visualise the heatmap of the matrix with all
hyperparameters set to <span class="math inline">\(1\)</span>:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot_covariance(matrix = mat_rat_quad)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
<p>And with <span class="math inline">\(\alpha = 0.1\)</span> as a
comparison:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot_covariance(matrix = mat_rat_quad3)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
</div>
<div id="periodic-kernel" class="section level2" number="4.3">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.3</span> Periodic kernel</h2>
<p>Since we are interested in time series in this post, it would make
sense to introduce some kernels which capture properties that are common
in temporal data. One of these is seasonality (i.e., broad periodic
patterns which repeat at regular intervals). We can capture this through
a periodic kernel (also known as an ‘exponentiated sine squared’
kernel):</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
k(x, x&#39;) = \sigma^{2} \text{exp} \left(
-\frac{2}{\mathcal{l}^{2}}\text{sin}^{2} \left( \pi\frac{|x -
x&#39;|}{p} \right) \right)
\]</span></p>
<p>where <span class="math inline">\(\sigma^{2}\)</span> is the variance
(or amplitude in this case), <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{l}\)</span> is the lengthscale, and <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span> is the period (distance between
repetitions). We can sometimes determine <span class="math inline">\(p\)</span> beforehand by either eyeballing the
time-series plot, or numerically decomposing the data and determining
periods using a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_transform">Fourier
transform</a>. We will just use <span class="math inline">\(p =
1\)</span> here for demonstration.</p>
<p>We can code this kernel in R as:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>cppFunction(&quot;
NumericMatrix cov_periodic(NumericVector xa, NumericVector xb, double sigma, double l, double p) {
  int n1 = xa.size();
  int n2 = xb.size();
  NumericMatrix K(n1, n2);
  
  for (int i = 0; i &lt; n1; ++i) {
    for (int j = 0; j &lt; n2; ++j) {
      double diff = std::abs(xa[i] - xb[j]);
      double sin_term = std::sin(M_PI * diff / p);
      double exp_term = std::exp(-2 / pow(l, 2) * std::pow(sin_term, 2));
      K(i, j) = pow(sigma, 2) * exp_term;
    }
  }
  
  return K;
}
&quot;)</code></pre>
<p>Here is a sample of the matrix:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_periodic &lt;- cov_periodic(x1, x1, 1, 2, 1)
mat_periodic[1:5, 1:5]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##           [,1]      [,2]      [,3]      [,4]      [,5]
## [1,] 1.0000000 0.9920192 0.9689545 0.9332646 0.8885240
## [2,] 0.9920192 1.0000000 0.9920192 0.9689545 0.9332646
## [3,] 0.9689545 0.9920192 1.0000000 0.9920192 0.9689545
## [4,] 0.9332646 0.9689545 0.9920192 1.0000000 0.9920192
## [5,] 0.8885240 0.9332646 0.9689545 0.9920192 1.0000000</code></pre>
<p>And some random samples from the kernel:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>p2 &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_periodic), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_periodic)
print(p2)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Notice the cyclic nature? This is what enables us to capture
seasonality in time series.</p>
<p>Here is the heatmap (how cool is it seeing periodicity in this
format!):</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot_covariance(matrix = mat_periodic)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
</div>
<div id="white-noise-kernel" class="section level2" number="4.4">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">4.4</span> White noise
kernel</h2>
<p>The last common kernel we will introduce here is the white noise
kernel. This does exactly as you might expect — incorporates independent
and identically-distributed (i.i.d.) noise into the GP. Mathematically,
it is simple:</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
k(x, x&#39;) = \sigma^{2}I_{n}
\]</span></p>
<p>where <span class="math inline">\(\sigma^{2}\)</span> is the variance
of the noise and <span class="math inline">\(I_{n}\)</span> is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_matrix">identity matrix</a>
(a matrix of ones on the diagonal and zeros everywhere else — kind of
like the number one but for matrices). This kernel produces a matrix
that has zeros everywhere except the diagonal, which now contains the
variances.</p>
<p>We can code this in R as:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#&#39; White noise covariance function
#&#39; @param x \code{numeric} vector
#&#39; @param sigma \code{numeric} scalar denoting variance. Defaults to \code{1}
#&#39; @returns an object of class \code{matrix}
#&#39; 

cov_noise &lt;- function(x, sigma = 1){
  k &lt;- sigma * diag(length(x))
  return(k)
}</code></pre>
<p>Here is a sample of the matrix:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mat_white_noise &lt;- cov_noise(x = x1, sigma = 0.01)
mat_white_noise[1:5, 1:5]</code></pre>
<pre><code>##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,] 0.01 0.00 0.00 0.00 0.00
## [2,] 0.00 0.01 0.00 0.00 0.00
## [3,] 0.00 0.00 0.01 0.00 0.00
## [4,] 0.00 0.00 0.00 0.01 0.00
## [5,] 0.00 0.00 0.00 0.00 0.01</code></pre>
<p>And some random samples from the kernel:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>p3 &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mat_white_noise), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = x1, Sigma = mat_white_noise)
print(p3)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>And the heatmap (with zero highlighting, as we would expect from
white noise):</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot_covariance(matrix = mat_white_noise)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
<p><em>Side note: You may have picked up that every covariance function
introduced here has the parameter </em> <span class="math inline">\(\sigma^{2}\)</span> <em>out front. This parameter
acts as a scaling factor. By increasing its value, we can increase the
contribution of a given covariance function to the model.</em></p>
</div>
</div>
<div id="in-the-time-series-context" class="section level1" number="5">
<h1><span class="header-section-number">5</span> In the time series
context</h1>
<p>Now for the key piece of information:</p>
<p><strong>GPs are not limited to a single kernel. We can combine
kernels through multiplication or addition to generate a final kernel
that captures all the dynamics as we need.</strong></p>
<p>Here is where the structural time series decomposition idea comes in.
Using GPs, we can apply the same logic: summing or multiplying different
kernels that capture different statistical properties of our data can
produce a model that appropriately understands the various dynamics.
Summation of kernels can be thought of as an <em>OR</em> procedure,
while multiplication can be thought of as an <em>AND</em> procedure.
Looking at our original time-series data again, we have a linearly
increasing trend, seasonality, and noise. If we can define a kernel that
defines and combines these individual components, we <em>should</em> be
able to construct a GP that can model the data with reasonable
accuracy.</p>
<div id="preparing-the-covariance-function" class="section level2" number="5.1">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.1</span> Preparing the
covariance function</h2>
<p>We will start with the trend kernel. We know in our case that the
trend itself linear, but for posterity (pun intended), we will use a
squared exponential kernel anyway as it can model long-term smooth
effects that may not necessarily be linear in other applications. Recall
we coded this earlier as <code>cov_exp_quad</code>.</p>
<p>Next we will add a periodic kernel, as we know there is periodicity
in our data. In our case, since we simulated the data, we know the
period (<span class="math inline">\(p\)</span> in the kernel) is <span class="math inline">\(2 \times 4 \times \pi \approx 25\)</span>, so we
can be pretty confident that <span class="math inline">\(p = 25\)</span>
is a good option. In practice, we would need to numerically determine
the period (or maybe 2 or more if we have multiple seasonalities) using
something like a Fourier transform.</p>
<p>We are also going to add a white noise kernel as we know there is
some error around the data (as we added noise to begin with through
<code>runif</code>). We can now compute the three covariance matrices,
and sum them for a final matrix which captures all the individual
dynamics:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>Sigma_exp_quad &lt;- cov_exp_quad(y, y, 1, length(y))
Sigma_periodic &lt;- cov_periodic(y, y, 1, 1, 25)
Sigma_white_noise &lt;- cov_noise(x = 1:nrow(Sigma_exp_quad), sigma = 0.01)
Sigma_comb &lt;- Sigma_exp_quad + Sigma_periodic + Sigma_white_noise</code></pre>
<p>As a bonus, I mentioned earlier we can detect periods in data using a
Fourier transform. Here is one example of how we can find the most
important period in our data using a Fourier transform from the
<code>TSA</code> package:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>peri &lt;- TSA::periodogram(y, plot = FALSE) # Do Fourier transform to decompose signal
dd &lt;- data.frame(freq = peri$freq, spec = peri$spec) # Extract frequency and spectral value
order &lt;- dd[order(-dd$spec),] # Rearrange to descending order
time &lt;- 1 / order$f # Convert frequency to original scale (i.e., &quot;timepoint&quot; index)
time &lt;- time[!time %in% length(y)] # Remove length of y from as it&#39;s not informative
time[1]</code></pre>
<pre><code>## [1] 25</code></pre>
<p>As we see, we get <span class="math inline">\(p = 25\)</span>, the
same period value we knew from the parameters of our simulated data.
Hopefully this demonstrates to you how we can numerically test for
periods on unknown data.</p>
</div>
<div id="sampling-from-the-prior" class="section level2" number="5.2">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.2</span> Sampling from the
prior</h2>
<p>Bada bing, bada boom<a href="#fn1" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref1"><sup>1</sup></a> our full covariance function is specified,
our data is ready to go, and we are now ready to specify our full GP!
Well… sort of. We are first going to draw samples from the GP
<em>prior</em> to visualise a bunch of different candidate functions
<em>before</em> we account for any actual data:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>p4 &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(Sigma_comb), k = 5, mu = NULL, X = y, Sigma = Sigma_comb)
print(p4)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>This is starting to look more like a time series!</p>
<p>We can also visualise the heatmap:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>plot_covariance(matrix = Sigma_comb) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c()</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="576" /></p>
<p>Clearly we still have some work to do, but it’s nice to know our
prior is in the ballpark. Now we can incorporate the actual data
(<em>likelihood</em>) and compute the thing of interest — the
<em>posterior</em>.</p>
</div>
<div id="predicting-from-the-posterior" class="section level2" number="5.3">
<h2><span class="header-section-number">5.3</span> Predicting from the
posterior</h2>
<p>To reiterate, we are trying to predict <span class="math inline">\(\mathbf{y}_{2} = f(X_{2})\)</span> points for
<span class="math inline">\(n_{2}\)</span> new samples using our GP
prior and <span class="math inline">\(n_{1}\)</span> datapoints (<span class="math inline">\((X_{1}, \mathbf{y}_{1})\)</span>):</p>
<p><span class="math display">\[
\left[\begin{array}{c} \mathbf{y}_{1} \\ \mathbf{y}_{2}
\end{array}\right]
\sim
\mathcal{N} \left(
\left[\begin{array}{c} \mu_{1} \\ \mu_{2} \end{array}\right],
\left[ \begin{array}{cc}
\Sigma_{11} &amp; \Sigma_{12} \\
\Sigma_{21} &amp; \Sigma_{22}
\end{array} \right]
\right)
\]</span></p>
<p>We can summarise this using conditional probability for the posterior
distribution: <span class="math inline">\(p(\mathbf{y}_{2} | \;
\mathbf{y}_{1}, X_{1}, X_{2})\)</span>.</p>
<p>Remember that <span class="math inline">\(\mu_{1} = m(X_{1})\)</span>
(mean function of <span class="math inline">\(n_{1} \times 1\)</span>
size) and <span class="math inline">\(\Sigma_{11} = k(X_{1},
X_{1})\)</span> (covariance function of size <span class="math inline">\(n_{1} \times n_{1}\)</span>) specifies our GP.
This can be broken down further to get the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conditional_probability">conditional
distributions</a>, but I will save you the linear algebra (see <a href="https://peterroelants.github.io/posts/gaussian-process-tutorial/">this
post</a> for a nice overview). However, it is this linear algebra that
makes GPs tricky to apply in practice, especially when our input data is
very large. GPs rely on computing the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invertible_matrix">inverse</a> of
covariance matrices, pushing their computation time to <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{O}(N^{3})\)</span> (compared to <span class="math inline">\(\mathcal{O}(N)\)</span> for standard Bayesian
linear regression). Keep this in mind if you decide to use GPs in your
own work.</p>
<p>Before we define the GP itself, for ease and clarity, we are going to
define a simple function which automatically computes and sums the
covariance functions we want. Note that we are actually going to add
noise in the GP function itself for computational stability reasons.
There are much more flexible and extensible ways to define a composite
kernel, but the method below is simple for our purposes.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#&#39; Additive kernel of exponentiated quadratic, periodic, and white noise
#&#39; @param xa \code{numeric} vector of input data
#&#39; @param xb \code{numeric} vector of data to predict for
#&#39; @param sigma_1 \code{numeric} scalar denoting the variance of \code{cov_exp_quad}. Defaults to \code{1}
#&#39; @param sigma_2 \code{numeric} scalar denoting the variance of \code{cov_periodic}. Defaults to \code{1}
#&#39; @param l_1 \code{numeric} scalar denoting the lengthscale of \code{cov_exp_quad}. Defaults to \code{1}
#&#39; @param l_2 \code{numeric} scalar denoting the lengthscale of \code{cov_periodic}. Defaults to \code{1}
#&#39; @param p \code{numeric} scalar denoting the period of \code{cov_periodic}. Defaults to \code{1}
#&#39; @returns an object of class \code{matrix}
#&#39; 

cov_summed &lt;- function(xa, xb, sigma_1 = 1, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 1, l_2 = 1, p = 1){
  Sigma_exp_quad &lt;- cov_exp_quad(xa, xb, sigma_1, l_1)
  Sigma_periodic &lt;- cov_periodic(xa, xb, sigma_2, l_2, p)
  Sigma &lt;- Sigma_exp_quad + Sigma_periodic
  return(Sigma)
}</code></pre>
<p>Okay, we can now define our GP function to calculate the posterior
mean vector and covariance matrix. We are going to predict values for a
set of evenly-spaced time points across the <span class="math inline">\([1-100]\)</span> domain.</p>
<pre class="r"><code>#&#39; Calculate posterior mean vector and covariance matrix
#&#39; @param x \code{numeric} vector of input data
#&#39; @param xprime \code{numeric} vector of data points to predict
#&#39; @param y \code{numeric} vector values to learn from
#&#39; @param sigma \code{numeric} scalar denoting variance of the noise kernel. Defaults to \code{0.05}
#&#39; @param cov_function \code{function} which calculates the additive covariance matrix
#&#39; @param ... covariance function hyperparameters to be passed to the covariance functions within \code{cov_function}
#&#39; @return \code{GaussProc} object containing the input data, posterior mean function and covariance matrix
#&#39;

GP &lt;- function(x, xprime, y, sigma = 0.05, cov_function, ...){
  Sigma_11 &lt;- cov_function(x, x, ...) + diag(sigma ^ 2, length(x))
  Sigma_12 &lt;- cov_function(x, xprime, ...)
  Sigma_inv &lt;- t(solve(Sigma_11, Sigma_12))
  Sigma_22 &lt;- cov_function(xprime, xprime, ...)
  Sigma_2 &lt;- Sigma_22 - (Sigma_inv %*% Sigma_12) # Posterior covariance matrix
  mu_2 &lt;- Sigma_inv %*% y # Posterior mean vector
  gp &lt;- list(x, xprime, y, mu_2, Sigma_2)
  names(gp) &lt;- c(&quot;x&quot;, &quot;xprime&quot;, &quot;y&quot;, &quot;mu&quot;, &quot;Sigma&quot;)
  gp &lt;- structure(gp, class = c(&quot;GaussProc&quot;, &quot;list&quot;))
  return(gp)
}

# Run the function

mod &lt;- GP(x = 1:length(y), xprime = seq(from = 1, to = 100, by = 10), 
         y = y, sigma = 0.8, cov_function = cov_summed, 
         sigma_1 = 5, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 75, l_2 = 1, p = 25)</code></pre>
<p>Now that we have our mean vector and covariance matrix for our
posterior distribution, we can do useful things, such as sample draws
from it and summarise it in terms of the posterior mean and credible
interval (which we will set to <span class="math inline">\(95\%\)</span>, <a href="https://xcelab.net/rm/statistical-rethinking/">though there is
much discussion about the appropriate interval for Bayesian
posteriors</a>). We are going to define a function to do some of the
same data frame wrangling we have done before and draw a plot to
visualise model predictions against the input data. Again, this code is
mostly just preparatory and visualisation stuff — the actual draws from
the posterior is one line of code:</p>
<p><code>posterior &lt;- as.data.frame(t(MASS::mvrnorm(n = draws, mu = x$mu, Sigma = x$Sigma)))</code></p>
<pre class="r"><code>#&#39; Plot summary of draws from GP posterior
#&#39; @param x \code{GaussProc} object
#&#39; @param data \code{data.frame} containing time points and \code{y} values
#&#39; @param draws \code{integer} denoting the number of draws from the posterior. Defaults to \code{100}
#&#39; @param ... arguments to be passed to methods
#&#39; @return object of class \code{ggplot}
#&#39;

plot.GaussProc &lt;- function(x, data, draws = 100, ...){
  
  stopifnot(inherits(x, &quot;GaussProc&quot;) == TRUE)
  
  # Generate dataframe of draws from posterior
  
  thenames &lt;- list()
    
  for(i in 1:draws){
    thenames[[i]] &lt;- paste0(&quot;Sample &quot;, i)
  }
  
  thenames &lt;- unlist(thenames)
  posterior &lt;- as.data.frame(t(MASS::mvrnorm(n = draws, mu = x$mu, Sigma = x$Sigma)))
  colnames(posterior) &lt;- thenames
  
  posterior &lt;- posterior %&gt;%
    mutate(timepoint = x$xprime) %&gt;%
    pivot_longer(cols = 1:ncol(posterior), names_to = &quot;sample&quot;, values_to = &quot;y&quot;)
  
  posterior_mean &lt;- posterior %&gt;%
    reframe(mu = mean(y), .by = &quot;timepoint&quot;)

  posterior_sd &lt;- data.frame(timepoint = x$xprime,
                             sigma = sqrt(diag(x$Sigma))) # SD is square root of variance

  posterior_summary &lt;- merge(x = posterior_mean, y = posterior_sd, by = &quot;timepoint&quot;)
  multiplier &lt;- 1.96 # Multiplier for 95% interval over normal distribution
  posterior_summary$lower &lt;- posterior_summary$mu - (multiplier * posterior_summary$sigma)
  posterior_summary$upper &lt;- posterior_summary$mu + (multiplier * posterior_summary$sigma)
  
  # Draw plot
  
  p &lt;- ggplot(data = posterior_summary) +
    geom_ribbon(aes(x = timepoint, ymin = lower, ymax = upper), fill = nous_colour(&quot;S5&quot;), alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_line(data = data, aes(x = timepoint, y = y), colour = nous_colour(&quot;C5&quot;)) +
    geom_point(data = data, aes(x = timepoint, y = y), colour = nous_colour(&quot;C5&quot;)) +
    geom_line(aes(x = timepoint, y = mu), colour = nous_colour(&quot;S5&quot;), size = 1) +
    labs(title = &quot;Posterior mean and 95% prediction interval&quot;,
         subtitle = paste0(&quot;Interval calculated over &quot;, draws, &quot; samples&quot;),
         x = &quot;Timepoint&quot;,
         y = &quot;Value&quot;) +
    theme_nous(gridlines = TRUE)
  
  return(p)
}

# Apply function

p6 &lt;- plot(mod, data = tmp, 100)
print(p6)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Very cool! Our model clearly has <em>learnt</em> the right
composition of dynamics from the input data in that it follows the data
reasonably closely. However there are a couple of concerns:</p>
<ul>
<li>The <span class="math inline">\(95\%\)</span> prediction interval is
pretty narrow — Our model is very confident in the numbers despite not
matching the <span class="math inline">\(y\)</span> values exactly. This
is mildly worrisome, and may call for re-parameterisation with increased
uncertainty, or other considerations</li>
<li>The model underestimates many of the “peak” values in the cycles and
overestimates the “trough” values — This isn’t the case for all, but it
is common enough to warrant further exploration (and potentially
re-parameterisation)</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Remember: Model fitting, evaluation, and re-parameterisation is
all part of the modelling process! Very rarely do we land a final model
first go. This iterative approach to statistical modelling ensures you
are in-the-loop the whole time, making active decisions that can be
defended by empirical evidence, theory, or domain knowledge.</em></p>
<p>The above model examined ten uniformally distributed time points
across our available domain. How well does our model do if we predicted
for 20?</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mod2 &lt;- GP(x = 1:length(y), xprime = seq(from = 1, to = 100, by = 5),
           y = y, sigma = 0.8, cov_function = cov_summed, 
           sigma_1 = 5, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 75, l_2 = 1, p = 25)

p7 &lt;- plot(mod2, tmp, 100)
print(p7)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>What about all 100 time points?</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mod3 &lt;- GP(x = 1:length(y), xprime = 1:length(y),
           y = y, sigma = 0.8, cov_function = cov_summed, 
           sigma_1 = 5, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 75, l_2 = 1, p = 25)

p8 &lt;- plot(mod3, tmp, 100)
print(p8)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>How about if we increased the noise scaling factor (i.e.,
uncertainty)?</p>
<pre class="r"><code>mod4 &lt;- GP(x = 1:length(y), xprime = 1:length(y),
           y = y, sigma = 1.2, cov_function = cov_summed, 
           sigma_1 = 5, sigma_2 = 1, l_1 = 75, l_2 = 1, p = 25)

p9 &lt;- plot(mod4, tmp, 100)
print(p9)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Intuitively, we see that the prediction intervals widen (i.e., become
more uncertain) with the greater inclusion of noise. Keep in mind that
if we used an actual GP tool, hyperparameter optimisation would usually
be performed for all covariance function parameters through a method
such as marginal maximum likelihood.</p>
<p>Lastly, just like with the GP prior, we can also sample individual
realisations from the posterior. Our above method of summarising a <span class="math inline">\(\pm1.96\sigma\)</span> prediction interval
essentially does this over a large range, but seeing how individual
realisations progress from the prior stage where they do not fit the
shape of our data to the posterior stage where each realisation is a
feasible data generating function for our observations is really
cool:</p>
<pre class="r"><code>p10 &lt;- sample_kernel(n = nrow(mod4$Sigma), k = 5, X = mod4$x, mu = mod4$mu, Sigma = mod4$Sigma) +
  labs(title = &quot;5 realisations of the posterior distribution&quot;)

print(p10)</code></pre>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>And there we have it. A GP from scratch that can model time-series
data with trend, seasonality, and noise in an interpretable way<a href="#fn2" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref2"><sup>2</sup></a>.</p>
</div>

Gaussian processes in your own time series work. For more information,
